SIMPLE: sentence
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sentence
<hw>Sen"tence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from L.
<ets>sententia</ets>, for <ets>sentientia</ets>, from <ets>sentire</ets>
to discern by the senses and the mind, to feel, to think. See
<er>Sense</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Sentiensi</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Sense; meaning; significance.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tales of best <qex>sentence</qex> and most solace.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The discourse itself, voluble enough, and full of
<qex>sentence</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An opinion; a decision; a
determination; a judgment, especially one of an unfavorable
nature.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My <qex>sentence</qex> is for open war.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That by them [Luther's works] we may pass <qex>sentence</qex> upon
his doctrines.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A philosophical or theological opinion; a dogma;
<as>as, Summary of the <ex>Sentences</ex>; Book of the
<ex>Sentences</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>In civil and admiralty law, the
judgment of a court pronounced in a cause; in criminal and
ecclesiastical courts, a judgment passed on a criminal by a court or
judge; condemnation pronounced by a judicial tribunal; doom. In common
law, the term is exclusively used to denote the judgment in criminal
cases.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Received the <qex>sentence</qex> of the law.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A short saying, usually containing moral
instruction; a maxim; an axiom; a saw.</def>
<rj><au>Broome.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A combination of words which is
complete as expressing a thought, and in writing is marked at the close
by a period, or full point. See <er>Proposition</er>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Sentences</xex> are simple or compound. A simple
sentence consists of one subject and one finite verb; as, ⟦ldquo⟧The
Lord reigns.⟦rdquo⟧ A compound sentence contains two or more subjects
and finite verbs, as in this verse: -</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He fills, he bounds, connects, and equals all.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dark sentence</b></col>, <cd>a saying not easily
explained.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A king . . . understanding <qex>dark sentences</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dan. vii. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sentence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sentence
<hw>Sen"tence</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sentenced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sentencing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
pass or pronounce judgment upon; to doom; to condemn to punishment; to
prescribe the punishment of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature herself is <qex>sentenced</qex> in your doom.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To decree or announce as a sentence.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To utter sententiously.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Feltham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sentence method</ent>⟦br⟧
